#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:18
#: ../../incident-intelligence/respond-manage-incidents/respond-to-incident.rst:21
msgid "Acknowledged"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:19
msgid ""
"Incident responders select this status to indicate that they are aware of"
" the incident. The status lifecycle for incidents is triggered, then "
"acknowledged, and then resolved. Acknowledging an incident prevents the "
"escalation to the next step in an incident workflow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:21
msgid "Alert"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:22
msgid "An alert is an event that meets a defined threshold or criteria."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:25
msgid ""
"Use alert grouping to automate incident trigger conditions and group "
"alerts. Alert grouping conditions are set up at the incident-policy level"
" to let you customize the grouping rules for each incident policy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:28
msgid ""
"Alert routing associates alerts with an incident policy. If an alert "
"matches your configured alert routing conditions, it is routed to the "
"incident policy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:30
msgid "Detector"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:31
msgid ""
"Use a detector to specify the events for which you want to create an "
"alert that is ingested into Incident Intelligence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:33
#: ../../incident-intelligence/respond-manage-incidents/respond-to-incident.rst:24
msgid "Dismissed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:34
msgid ""
"An incident status that incident responders can set to indicate that the "
"incident is dismissed. The status lifecycle for incidents is triggered, "
"then acknowledged, and then resolved. Setting an incident status to "
"dismissed prevents the escalation to the next step in an incident "
"workflow. When you dismiss an incident, it is considered invalid and "
"closed; you will no longer be able to make updates to the incident."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:36
msgid "Incident Management"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:37
msgid ""
"The entire configuration process for an incident policy in Incident "
"Intelligence. This is where you create an incident policy and configure "
"alert routing, alert grouping, and incident workflows for incidents "
"associated with an incident policy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:39
msgid "Incident"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:40
msgid ""
"An unplanned interruption to a service or reduction in the quality of a "
"service that needs to be resolved. Each incident is made up of alerts "
"that are ingested into Incident Intelligence. You can also create "
"incidents manually. Manual incidents don't have ingested alerts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:42
msgid "Incident action"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:43
msgid ""
"Any status-changing event taken by a user or the system on an incident. "
"Incident responders can acknowledge, resolve, or dismiss an incident. "
"These actions update the incident status to reflect the most recent "
"action."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:45
msgid "Incident alerting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:46
msgid ""
"The primary mechanism of Incident Intelligence. It is the process by "
"which alerts and events are ingested at scale and grouped to create "
"incidents. As alerts and events are ingested into Incident Intelligence, "
"they pass through a series of data transformations, such as alert routing"
" and alert grouping."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:48
msgid "Incident policy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:49
msgid ""
"Incident policies let you organize incidents depending on the impacted "
"component in your environment. Incident policies include alert-routing "
"and alert-grouping rules and an incident workflow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:51
msgid "Incident status"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:52
msgid ""
"Where an incident is in its lifecycle. The status of an incident changes "
"based on alert grouping conditions, as well as actions from a user. "
"Throughout the lifecycle of an incident, the incident status can go from "
"triggered, to acknowledged, to resolved or dismissed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:54
msgid "Incident workflow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:55
msgid ""
"A configurable series of escalation steps that run in response to a "
"triggered incident. Incident workflows determine who is notified of an "
"incident and the time interval for notifications. You can also use "
"incident workflows to manage how incidents are routed, add automation "
"steps, and route to an on-call schedule."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:57
msgid "Maintenance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:58
msgid ""
"An incident policy status that mutes all associated incidents. Use "
"incident policy maintenance for planned outages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:60
#: ../../incident-intelligence/respond-manage-incidents/mtta-mttr.rst:30
msgid "Mean time to acknowledge (MTTA)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:61
msgid ""
"The average time it takes from when an incident is triggered to when the "
"incident is acknowledged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:63
#: ../../incident-intelligence/respond-manage-incidents/mtta-mttr.rst:33
msgid "Mean time to resolve (MTTR)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:64
msgid ""
"The average time it takes from when an incident is triggered to when the "
"incident is resolved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:66
msgid "Muted"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:67
msgid ""
"An incident status that is set when the associated incident policy is put"
" into maintenance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:69
msgid "Notification preference"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:70
msgid ""
"A user-level preference that specifies how the user wants to be notified "
"of incidents when they are on call. Notification methods include email, "
"mobile push, SMS, and voice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:72
msgid "On-call schedules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:73
msgid ""
"An on-call schedule consists of one or more shifts, with members who "
"rotate through a shift. Use an on-call schedule as a step in your "
"incident policies' incident workflows."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:75
#: ../../incident-intelligence/respond-manage-incidents/respond-to-incident.rst:27
msgid "Resolved"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:76
msgid ""
"An incident status that incident responders set to indicate that the "
"incident is resolved. The status lifecycle for incidents is triggered, "
"then acknowledged, and then resolved. Resolving an incident status "
"prevents the escalation to the next step in an incident workflow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:78
msgid "Incident policy-based routing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../incident-intelligence/key-concepts.rst:79
msgid ""
"Incident Intelligence relies on an incident policy-based routing scheme. "
"Incident policy-based routing automatically organizes and routes "
"incidents depending on the service that itâ€™s impacting. Rather than "
"routing to a combination of teams and policies, the incident policy an "
"incident is associated with determines who is notified of the incident."
msgstr ""

